(1,$title$The Lunch Table Map$title$,$body$Maya noticed the problem before anyone said it aloud. In Plano school cafeteria, a new student stood alone with a tray. The room seemed to pause around paper map of the cafeteria, as if even ordinary things were waiting for a choice. A small worry tapped at Maya's thoughts, steady as rain on a window.

At first, Maya wanted the problem to belong to someone else. That would have been easier. But the longer Maya watched, the smaller that easy answer felt. So Maya took a breath and invited the student to help draw a better map. The first try was awkward, and a few people looked over, but no one laughed. Instead, the silence loosened, and the problem began to look like something ordinary hands could fix.

By the end, the map became a list of open seats instead of closed groups. Maya walked away feeling lighter. The day had not become perfect, but it had turned, like a page, toward something kinder. Later, when Maya remembered the moment, the important part was not being brave right away. It was choosing to act while still feeling unsure.$body$,'literary'::map_passage_genre,188,700,'191_200'::map_rit_band,'original',$topic$G4 passage seed 2026-04-30: school friendship: lunch table choice$topic$),
(2,$title$The Cricket Over the Fence$title$,$body$Aarav noticed the problem before anyone said it aloud. In a Plano backyard, the tennis ball kept bouncing into Mrs. Patel's flower bed. The room seemed to pause around a chalk line for the boundary, as if even ordinary things were waiting for a choice. A small worry tapped at Aarav's thoughts, steady as rain on a window.

At first, Aarav wanted the problem to belong to someone else. That would have been easier. But the longer Aarav watched, the smaller that easy answer felt. So Aarav took a breath and changed the rules so careful aim mattered more than power. The first try was awkward, and a few people looked over, but no one laughed. Instead, the silence loosened, and the problem began to look like something ordinary hands could fix.

By the end, his younger cousin won the final point with a soft tap. Aarav walked away feeling lighter. The day had not become perfect, but it had turned, like a page, toward something kinder. Later, when Aarav remembered the moment, the important part was not being brave right away. It was choosing to act while still feeling unsure.$body$,'literary'::map_passage_genre,191,790,'201_210'::map_rit_band,'original',$topic$G4 passage seed 2026-04-30: family cricket: younger cousin helps$topic$),
(3,$title$Grandmother Tries Tacos$title$,$body$Priya noticed the problem before anyone said it aloud. In her grandmother's kitchen, Grandmother said tacos were too messy to be supper. The room seemed to pause around a warm tortilla, as if even ordinary things were waiting for a choice. A small worry tapped at Priya's thoughts, steady as rain on a window.

