(7,$title$A Quiet Seat for Theo$title$,$body$Imani noticed the problem before anyone said it aloud. In a fourth-grade classroom, Theo kept staring at his closed notebook. The room seemed to pause around a sharpened blue pencil, as if even ordinary things were waiting for a choice. A small worry tapped at Imani's thoughts, steady as rain on a window.

At first, Imani wanted the problem to belong to someone else. That would have been easier. But the longer Imani watched, the smaller that easy answer felt. So Imani took a breath and placed the pencil beside him without making a speech. The first try was awkward, and a few people looked over, but no one laughed. Instead, the silence loosened, and the problem began to look like something ordinary hands could fix.

